## Why Not Direct API Calls?

If you used `fetch()` directly, you'd have to handle:

❌ **Session tokens** - Generate unique tokens, track them across suggest/retrieve calls  
❌ **Debouncing** - Implement 300ms delays manually  
❌ **Race conditions** - Cancel old requests when new ones start  
❌ **Error handling** - API timeouts, rate limits, network issues  
❌ **Request optimization** - Avoid duplicate calls  

Search JS Core handles ALL of this automatically while still giving you complete UI control.

## Key Benefits of This Approach

✅ **Complete customization** - Your design, your keyboard nav, your styling  
✅ **Production-ready** - No manual session token or debouncing bugs  
✅ **Cleaner code** - Focus on UI, not API complexity  
✅ **Better performance** - Optimized request handling  
✅ **Easier maintenance** - Less code to maintain  

This gives you the best of both worlds: complete UI control with production-ready search functionality.

Here's how to handle building taps and highlight them using Mapbox's modern Featureset Interactions API with the Standard style:

## View System Implementation

```kotlin
import com.mapbox.maps.interactions.ClickInteraction
import com.mapbox.maps.interactions.featuresets.StandardBuildingsState

class MapActivity : AppCompatActivity() {
    private lateinit var mapView: MapView

    override fun onCreate(savedInstanceState: Bundle?) {
        super.onCreate(savedInstanceState)
        setContentView(R.layout.activity_map)

        mapView = findViewById(R.id.mapView)
        mapView.mapboxMap.loadStyle(Style.STANDARD)

        setupBuildingInteractions()
    }

    private fun setupBuildingInteractions() {
        // Add building tap interaction
        mapView.mapboxMap.addInteraction(
            ClickInteraction.standardBuildings { building, context ->
                Log.d("MapTap", "Tapped building with ID: ${building.id}")

                // Highlight the tapped building
                mapView.mapboxMap.setFeatureState(
                    building,
                    StandardBuildingsState {
                        highlight(true)
                    }
                )

                true // Stop event propagation
            }
        )
    }

    override fun onStart() {
        super.onStart()
        mapView.onStart()
    }

    override fun onStop() {
        super.onStop()
        mapView.onStop()
    }

    override fun onDestroy() {
        super.onDestroy()
        mapView.onDestroy()
    }
}
```

